social_posts.post_text: Proof that snow exists in SoCal 😜. I’ve been missing winter lately, so @larj_marj and I got up well before dawn to go shred some surprisingly good snow in the San Bernadino Mtns. Make time for things that feed your soul! ❄️

🌲🌴 A very LA Christmas 🥹.

Sometimes it’s still wild to me how quickly our lives can completely change, when the right thing comes along. And even though I’m missing snow and winter and 🇨🇦 right now, I wouldn’t trade this for the world. Lots to be thankful for this Xmas season.

Merry Christmas, friends. xx

Charlie Salami, living his best freaking life. Not too shabby, little rescue mutt.

✌️let’s go, 2023!

💕When Hilly met Billy.

If you didn’t watch the beautiful video about our story that @billyyang posted yesterday, well….spoiler 😜. 

We are incredibly grateful and overwhelmed by the love and support we’ve felt from our trail and life community. The past year and a half have taught me so much about what real love looks like, and more importantly about what happens when you consciously choose to live life as authentically and honestly as possible. 

It’s not about finding someone else to complete us. It’s about finding someone who already shares the same dreams that you do, and then supporting each other in chasing down those dreams — together. 

In the words of my love @billyyang: We get one take. Live it fully.

W I N T E R

There are seasons to everything. I remind myself of this a lot these days. Creating the time and energy needed to train for a big race is a privilege, not a guarantee. Having easy access to big, beautiful mountain spaces is also a privilege, and one that I’m presently missing.

I also recognize that my priorities have shifted. Building a home and future with my little family unit now feels more important than sending those big lines.

Life is a complex balancing act, isn’t it? Yearning for the freedom of those simple mountain days does not take away from where I am choosing to focus my energy now. They are just two sides of the same me, learning to coexist and find the right balance. And I know that when those perfect mountain days do come along again, I’ll only appreciate them more.

Photos from a truly spectacular backcountry ski day on the Sunshine Coast, BC.

Taking full advantage of winter this week in beautiful Colorado, and only slightly missing some oxygen trying to ski above 13,000ft 😅. 

Being a multi-sport athlete is super important to me, and I’m always so thankful for these glorious days in the backcountry. I may not get quite as many of them as I used to, but I sure do enjoy the hell out of the ones I get.

…When an every day trail run turns into a frolic in some seriously popping fields of wildflowers 🙈😍. A slight change from the gnarly summits and alpine skiing of last week, but I’ll take it.

So great to be out on the trails with @sawna again… thanks for the tour and the 🎥 🥰

Find yourself a tribe of badass, kickass women — and hold them tight. 

Happy every day to all of the incredible women in my life. You all inspire the hell out of me.

Fully in survival mode these days, but I never ever regret making time to catch a snowy sunny morning in the mountains…even if @sawna and I had to get up at 4am to make it happen. 

Also whoooo knew when I moved to LA that they’d surpass Seattle’s YEARLY rainfall average in less than 3 months🤣?? The fun part is seeing that translate into epic amounts of snow in the backyard mountains. Not exactly what you picture when you think of Los Angeles, eh?

C H A N G E 

It blows my mind how quickly life can pivot on us. Three years ago around this time, I was navigating a career-crushing pandemic and the simultaneous end of a long term relationship, while moving to a remote little town in British Columbia to be a hermit.

Now, @billyyang and I are currently elbows deep in moving chaos, downsizing our collective lives into a tiny, TINY home (more on that, soon), while juggling wedding and life plans simultaneously. If you’d told me then that I’d be living in Los Angeles with the Hollywood sign in my new backyard, I would have probably laughed in your face at the sheer improbability of that thought. 

Yet here we are. I’ve learned that change can be scary, and upending every aspect of my life has certainly been a daunting process. But if running these stupid long ultra distances over the last decade has taught me anything at all, it’s that I can absolutely do hard things. And the more I lean into that fear and dissect it, the more I realize the power in letting go and trusting in the journey. Because we have to enjoy the ride, don’t we? It can’t just be about “getting there” — because we never will, really. The goalposts are always moving. Always.

The process IS the purpose. It has to be.

👋 just dropping in to say hi. Funny how the busier our lives are, the quieter we get about sharing them, right? I can truly say that this season of life is an amazing one for me, although you wouldn’t know it by my online radio silence. I’m engaged to a truly wonderful man (looking at you @billyyang ) and we are building our lives together in a beautiful and intentional way with our ridiculous mutt who I love to death (that’s you, Charlie Salami🥹). Sometimes I think it’s easier to share when things aren’t going well, than when they are. Angst breeds art, to paraphrase a few greats. 

But it’s equally important to acknowledge and celebrate the seasons of joy. Too much of our lives are filled with fear-based content — because fear and drama are a very marketable commodity. But what if we make a choice to filter that out and find the joy in our lives and lean into it hard every day? It doesn’t mean that things aren’t difficult— I have some of that right now as well, don’t get me wrong. But we always get to choose how we spend our energy, or how we want to view the world. 

And I choose joy. If you practice it long enough, it just might become a habit. 

📸 my friend @ccracken, from a time when I lived in the woods in a little remote cottage and had no idea where my life was going to go next, because life is sure a wild ride 🙃

Four years ago today, @billyyang and I met for the first time at an Earth Day park cleanup event that he organized in LA. I happened to be in town visiting my friend @sawna and we randomly showed up to help. I couldn’t have told you in a MILLION years that four years later we’d be living together in Los Angeles, and getting married in a few short weeks. Life is a constant series of choices and opportunities, and we just never know which ones are going to totally change our lives. 

Happy Earth Day, friends. I happen to be an extra big fan of this day. 🥹

📸 @florisgierman

One of the hardest parts of moving to a new country was knowing that I’d be farther away from all the friends I’ve made throughout my life, and then embarking on the daunting task of making new ones in my new home. Seriously, how does one make friends as an adult?? It’s really not that easy to know where to even start. And yet having close friendships, especially female ones, is something I both value and need in my life. I am truly grateful for THESE wonderful women, who have quickly become my new community and family here in LA. Thank you for showing up, and for making me feel so very loved (and for throwing me the cutest little bridal shower ever). 💕

Happy birthday to my ride or die @billyyang. Life with you is one wonderful adventure full of love, laughter, and ridiculous shenanigans. I’ve never felt safer or more at home than I do with you, and it feels hard to believe that we get to keep doing this for a long, long time. Here’s to you on your birthday and every day, my love. 🥂

I realized lately that I don’t always do the best job of sharing my photos — and yet no matter how many new hats I wear these days on the video and production and design side of things, there’s a part of me that will always be a photographer first and foremost…constantly obsessed with freezing moments in a single frame. So f*ck the algorithms that tell us only clickbaity videos have any worth — I’m going to start posting more of what brings ME joy.

First up: in honour of @cocodona250 starting today and @destinationtrailraces Triple Crown registration opening, here’s a collection of some of my favourite moments from shooting 200 milers. ✨

Golden hour looks good on you, LA. 🥲

When I first became a photographer, I brought my DSLR with me everywhere. Every run, every random thing I was doing. All of my friends and their dogs were my muses — no one was safe. I’d carry my camera in my hand, trying to compensate with the rest of my body for the 6lb of metal I was awkwardly cradling, and doing a slight lean to the left to stay balanced. It didn’t do my running any favours, but it sure did teach me to think and move and change my settings on the fly as the conditions and lighting changed. Practice, practice, practice.

These days I’m a bit more selective with when I bring my camera along for the ride, but there are still times when it’s absolutely worth a bit of lopsided running just to do these fleeting moments justice. ✨

In this week’s episode of photos that I’ve never shared but very much adore, here’s a fun series with the one and only @zachmiller38 in Colorado from a little while back. 

**I’m not sure exactly what causes these crazy shades of red rocks (any geology majors here??), but it was off-the-charts gorgeous up there…and worth every bit of oxygen deprivation.

For my birthday this year, I traded last names 😜.

Birthdays are an interesting life check-in — a chance to reflect on time passing, and what we are doing with it. So many years I feel like I’m looking ahead to where I want to go next, but not this year. This year, I’m exactly where I want to be. I found my person in @billyyang, and all that matters now is eking the most out of this precious life together. As one of our wedding songs so beautifully says, “the time of our lives is all we have.” It’s a pretty wonderful place to be.

📸 absolutely gorgeous photos by @sarahattar

Courtney-freaking-Dauwalter. 

No words. Her win at @wser yesterday was historic, epic, and ceiling-smashing on so many levels. She took an hour and 18 minutes off of a historic course record set by @elliejgreenwood in 2012, placed 6th overall in what was also an extremely competitive men’s race, and took almost 2 hours off of her own winning @wser time from 2018. There really is no one quite like her. So freaking inspired and thrilled for you Court. A day to remember.

Photo dump from this year’s @wser.
What. A. Weekend.

I might sleep for a week now. 😴

It’s a bit crazy to think about how fast this month has gone, but holy crap @billyyang, we got married! Technically I guess you could even say that @wser was our honeymoon (at least for now). 

Finally getting a chance to go through some of the stunning photos that our dear friend @sarahattar shot for us, and obviously our wedding weekend wouldn’t be complete without starting it off with a few pre-aisle miles. Such a fun way to show all of our out-of-town friends the LA trails, and fun fact: this was the first run that Billy ever took me on in LA. Views or no views, it was still magical.

Life at Camp @hardrock100run so far has been a great success. 

This week each year for us is all about getting out in these gorgeous mountains, sharing good times with friends and getting our dirtbag camping on. It’s become an annual tradition for us — it’s where @billyyang and I first fell in love, and last year we very unexpectedly found Charlie Salami on day 2 of our road-trip back to Colorado, and he quickly became part of our little family. Always such a pleasure to be back.

Island Lake, San Juan Mountains. 2023 —> 2022 

Slight difference between this year and last year at Island Lake, and the snow is certainly going to make this year’s @hardrock100run spicy. But gosh darn it, it sure is pretty.

| Scenes from Tahoe 200 | 

Dear Sally,

You are braver and stronger than even you knew. You keep showing up even when you don’t think you possibly can anymore. And you keep inspiring the rest of us to see what we are capable of, too. 74 hours later, congrats on your podium finish at Tahoe 200. We are all so proud of you. ✨

Slightly belated, but happy one year “gotcha day” to our little rescue pup Charlie Salami 🥹. (You can check out the full story of how we found him on @billyyang’s YouTube channel if you haven’t seen it yet).

We love you so darn much, Bubs. Thanks for making our lives even better. 💕

📸 epic family portrait by @sarahattar

A very pleasant day spent on San Gorgonio (SoCal’s tallest peak!) with the hubs @billyyang. We are both trying to squeeze in training wherever we can for our back-to-back 100 mile races coming up in September… which seemed like a better idea when we signed up for them this spring. No one warned me how dangerous it is being married to someone who’s got equally terrible ideas of what’s “fun”. 😆

As always, thanks to @arcteryx.losangeles for keeping me ready to roll on the trails. LOVING the Norvan 7L trail vest, which is brand new this year. And of course, my beloved Norvan LD3’s, which are basically vibram-wrapped trail slippers for my feet.

Scenes from @utmbmontblanc week so far. 

Chamonix comes alive during this week every year, with cries of Allez Allez ringing out through the cobblestone streets, and epic crowds perched on the top of the surrounding mountains cheering on runners in dozens of languages. There’s something extra special about this communal and very international sharing of the things that we all love. Let’s go, runners!

Back in LA after a whirlwind 7 days in Chamonix, filled with some amazing people and memories (and the best surprise appearance I’ll probably ever pull on @billyyang in my life, see last slide). 

It felt like a very healthy balance of time, with large family-style meals, endless gelato and cheese, and some quality trail time in the alps ahead of my own upcoming 100 mile race (!!) all getting equal play. Life’s short, but if it’s well lived, it’s long enough. Pretty sure someone wise said that, and it rings very true these days. You’ve just got to go get it.

Earlier this year, @billyyang and I thought it would be a great idea to sign up for a “double header” set of 100 milers in September, starting with him running the iconic Wasatch 100 in Utah this past weekend, followed by me running the gnarly and mountainous IMTUF 100 in Idaho next weekend. 

Neither one of us realized just how busy our summers would get, and we’ve maybe spent a couple weekends total at home since the spring, between our wedding and back-to-back-to-back projects and events. It’s been amazing and fun and a whirlwind that we’ve loved sharing together, but to say that training for a pair of really hard 100 milers amidst our schedule has been tough would be a gross understatement.

We knew heading to Wasatch 100 just a few days after returning from Chamonix would be a stretch, but neither one of us anticipated how much of an impact the jet lag and lack of sleep would have on Billy’s race. I realized this pretty early on when Billy called me from mile 40, determined to drop after slogging through a pretty miserable first day where he was falling asleep on the trails just hours into his race (not a great start). I could feel his exhaustion in every fibre of his being, and part of me wanted to just let him end it early. It was as easy as just agreeing with him that it was a stupid idea to be doing this (it was) — and it would all be over.

But that’s not what we came for. And if there’s one thing I’ve learned in my decade of running ultras, it’s that we don’t get to choose what kind of day we get. And what sort of adventure would it be, if we only signed up wanting to experience the good parts? There’s no shortcuts to running 100 miles, it’s just really hard. But as @jasonkoop reminded me, it never always gets worse. And sometimes, you just have to feel it all to come out the other side.

Proud of you for gutting out your 34.5 hour finish, @billyyang. Hell of a rally, my love. With a whole lot of dirt naps along the way.

Next up, the Yangs head to Idaho. Let’s see what lessons IMTUF 100 has in store for me.

IMTUF 100 — where to start? This race has been on my bucket list for quite a few years now, and its reputation of being an impossibly difficult yet stunning mountain adventure did not disappoint. I’m really proud of this race, all told. @billyyang and I have had such a busy past six months, and I’ve had to work really hard to carve out the time for enough training to make it to the start line. This was the least amount of running volume I’ve ever done leading up to a 100 miler, but I tried my best to make every run count and prioritize quality over quantity, and I just had to hope that would be enough to carry me through.

My goals for this race were simple: I wanted to explore the beautiful mountains of Idaho (seriously 10/10 views), approach any problems or issues that came up in my race with curiousity and self-compassion (something that I’ve sometimes struggled to extend to myself in the past), and run with joy, appreciating the time I got to spend in the mountains with people I love (😘@billyyang and 💜@emilyhawgood). 

I had weird early-race leg cramping that showed up on the first climb of the race, and I realized quickly that I would have to slow way down and start practicing that self-compassion a lot sooner than expected. Runners streamed past me as I struggled to find my climbing legs, which is normally one of my strengths, and I focused on leaning into my gratitude for being out there at all. I was able to share some sections of trail with a few badass ladies, and that helped me stay positive and out of my own head. At my lowest point just before 50 miles, I decided to pull over to sit on a rock for 5 minutes, just soaking in the incredible views. It was a good way to reset, and I found myself moving lighter on the trails again. I really believe that running 100 miles is 20% physical and 80% mental, and this race was the perfect example of that. Emily joined me at mile 56 and we set off into the chilly but clear mountain night with renewed energy. The miles ticked off as we laughed, shared stories, and fell into creeks together. I even hilariously fell asleep on her while still moving, and woke up to her asking me if I was sleep walking. (Cont’d)

Billy joined me from mile 71 to 83, and I was so thankful that he was recovered enough from his own finish at Wasatch 100 last weekend to share some nighttime miles with me. We tackled the second to last climb together, which was a real doozy — straight up a rocky face, with a daunting view of headlamps in the distant hills ahead to remind me of how much climbing was yet to be done. We managed to mostly chat our way through it all, focusing on the time we got to spend together rather than how cold I was (it got very chilly), or how far I still had to go (far). Emily took over from mile 83 again and paced me till the finish (a long 104.5 miles), which also blew my mind considering she only just finished CCC herself. After my brief attempt at sleep walking on her, we rallied on the last climb and I finally started feeling strong enough to push, and not just survive. We hit the last aid station after what felt like several years of being sent down steep off-trail chutes, only to be sent back up equally implausible terrain again. I only asked Emily about 5x through this section if they had perhaps moved the aid station on us. Once we hit the last AS I knew it was mostly downhill to the finish, and I somehow found another gear to kick into. We flew down the single track, arbitrarily trying to finish under 30 hours (which those extra 4.5 miles ultimately didn’t allow, c’est la vie). It was so fun to open up a bit on this section, and Em gleefully egged me on with words of encouragement like “who needs legs, you don’t need to be able to walk tomorrow anyways!). It was the perfect way to end my long adventure in the mountains.

In the end, I finished in 30 hours and 16 minutes, 7th female overall in a field that included some really badass mountain women who I look up to tremendously (shoutout to @pixieninja44 on her win). Also a special shoutout to my buddy @davidrunsfar on his own IMTUF 100 finish, proud of you for gutting it out. 

100 miles is always stupidly far, but it’s the love I have for this community, the trails, and my people (@billyyang and @emilyhawgood, thank you doesn’t begin to convey my gratitude) that carries me through. 
I’m here for it all.

Life update! It has been an absolute whirlwind this last year, and I feel like I am just starting to emerge from the eye of the storm, although we still have another 6 weeks on the road before things truly slow down. In the past year I’ve moved countries, we moved into a tiny home (more on that another time), @billyyang and I got married, and then we quickly embarked on a crazy schedule of ultrarunning events that has now been going on for 4 months straight and counting. We recently figured out that we haven’t spent a single weekend at home in over 3 months, which is maybe why I feel like all I do is laundry and suitcase shuffling.

What’s surprised me the most about our chaotic schedule this year has been 1) how efficient you can be with your time when you don’t have much of it — we managed to even squeeze 100 miler training and some special moments with friends and family into the mix, and I’m proud of what we’ve managed to not compromise on. 2) It’s also been tremendously fun to get to do most of these adventures and projects with Billy (and Charlie Salami), and it’s reminded me that “home” will always be wherever my heart is…and those two hooligans sure have my heart. 

We are heading back to Vancouver today to see my family, and it’s crazy to think that it’s been almost a year since I was last there. I know in my heart that it will always feel like home, but it’s also nice to realize that where I’ve landed and the life Billy and I are building together also feels like home. The two can hold space in my heart together, and there’s nowhere else I’d rather be than where I am with him. That realization feels like the most special one of all.

Some special moments, captured by the wonderful @sarahattar

You’ve always got enough time for whatever you make time for.

Read it again. ✨

This is truly something I’ve learned to live by. It’s so easy to make excuses for why we don’t make time for the things we say we’d like to, but the truth is we’ve always got enough time — we just make constant choices about what we do with it. I’ve found it quite a fascinating phenomenon that the busier I am, the better I get at being intentional with my time. Like any habit, good or bad, the things we practice become the way we live.

📸 from a sneaky little backcountry overnighter with @haileyvandyk, where the sky decided to absolutely explode in a way I’ll never forget. Those bonus sunsets are always worth the work. 

#nowasteddays @arcteryx

Monday morning story time! I’ve been stopped more than a few times in grocery stores by random chemists who are awkwardly staring at my leg, or had people running behind me on a trail trying to dust off their high school chemistry to figure out what exactly the chemical compound is that’s tattooed on my leg. 

Most common guesses are either cocaine or caffeine — I’m not sure if it says more about me or about them, that they think I’d like to commemorate cocaine on my leg. Coffee, maybe. That’s not bad. But cocaine…Thanks??

At any rate, it’s neither. It’s actually the chemical structure for what has been isolated as the runner’s high, aka met-enkephalin. I got it tattooed on my leg in 2016 after I had a really crazy experience at a race, where I truly felt out-of-body for a fairly extended period of time. 

It was wild. 
Don’t do drugs, kids— just run long enough to hallucinate the same thing.

Anyways. There you have it! Also, it’s been raining here in LA lately, and I LOVE IT (altho it can never fully compete with my glorious PNW mud, pictured).

I didn’t start traveling seriously until I was in my early 20’s. In fact, the first time I was ever in an airplane was when I was 19 years old, and I was skydiving when that happened, so I didn’t even get to land in the darn thing.

The first really adventurous trip I ever went on was to Kenya, and that’s when I realized just how powerful traveling is. Not only was I blown away by the incredible culture, food, and landscapes of this beautiful part of Africa — but I also realized that I didn’t know shit about the world and what actually makes for a full, meaningful life. I’ve been hooked ever since, and my experiences in far-flung places all over the world have truly reshaped me. I’ve met the most wonderful, generous people, and been moved to tears by the sheer beauty of these places I get to explore. I also firmly believe that if we all pushed ourselves to experience life outside of our own comfort zones more, the world would be a far better and kinder place.

All that to say, travel and adventure have had a huge impact on my life, and I am very excited about the opportunity to start creating trips where I get to share those experiences with other amazing people. There’s a few days left to fill out a quick 2 minute survey for me, where I’m trying to nail down some of the top locations that people would like to explore with me. 
 
🙏 if you could take 2 minutes to fill out the survey, I would really appreciate it! (link in bio)

Photo dump from a whirlwind past few days spent chasing surprisingly great snow in Utah with a bunch of really great people. Just goes to show… you can take the Canadian out of Canada, but I’m always going to find my way to winter, wherever I am. 

Thanks @arcteryx.losangeles for always keeping me ready to play in the mtns, and to @martiskka for the epic first photo 💕

2023, you sure were a busy one 😅

Standout moments included:

✔️moving countries and homes (and phones)
✔️immigrating to the 🇺🇸 from 🇨🇦 
✔️marrying @billyyang (and changing my name, hello Yang!)
✔️at or involved in a LOT of ultra races
✔️IMTUF 100 finish
✔️much, much traveling
✔️many, many naps

I’m so grateful for all of the beautiful chaos. 2024 is going to hold a few more changes for me, and I’m excited to share some of those soon! In the meantime, 🥂 my friends. I hope you take some time to soak in and reflect on your own year, in all of its gritty, messy glory.
